ach religion as a multidimensional human phenomenon worthy of careful study.')}${card('Collaborative accountability','Projects are organized around defined roles, responsibilities, timelines, and outputs. Credit and leadership should reflect actual contributions to the work.')}${card('Ethical research','Research involving human participants must be conducted under appropriate ethical review and in accordance with applicable institutional, legal, and professional standards.')}</div></div></section>
<section class="section alt"><div class="shell prose"><h2>Organizational Home</h2><p>The Religious Cognition Collaborative operates as a sponsored research program. The exact legal nonprofit name and sponsor acknowledgment will be added after final authorization. The sponsoring nonprofit receives and administers grants and contributions on behalf of the Collaborative and provides financial and administrative oversight. RCC leadership directs the research agenda and develops projects in consultation with the investigators responsible for each project.</p><div class="notice">Sponsor name and approved logo pending final authorization.</div></div></section>`,
'/research':()=>`${hero('Research','RCC investigates religion as a cognitive, psychological, neural, social, and cultural phenomenon. Our work is organized around research questions rather than a single method or theoretical school. Projects may be empirical, computational, qualitative, or conceptual, depending on the problem being studied.')}
<section class="section"><div class="shell">${heading('Research Areas')}<div class="grid two">${card('Cognitive Science of Religion','We study the cognitive processes involved in religious concepts, beliefs, practices, and forms of reasoning. Relevant questions include how people represent supernatural agents, sacred objects, ritual efficacy, divine action, moral order, and religious identity.')}${card('Cognitive Neuroscience of Religion','We examine how distributed cognitive and neural systems contribute to religious belief, experience, practice, and social cognition. This work may include neuroimaging, behavioral neuroscience, psychophysiology, and the critical reanalysis of existing neuroscience claims.')}${card('Religious Experience and Consciousness','We investigate experiences interpreted as religious, spiritual, mystical, revelatory, or supernatural. Our work considers their phenomenology, cognitive structure, psychological context, interpretation, and consequences.')}${card('Dreams and Religious Cognition','We study how dreams may generate, simulate, organize, or transform religious concepts and experiences. This includes questions about supernatural agents, embodiment, emotion, memory, imagery, and the relationship between dream content and waking cognition.')}${card('Belief Formation, Development, and Transmission','We examine how religious beliefs and concepts are acquired, reinforced, revised, communicated, and transmitted. This includes developmental processes, social learning, narrative, ritual, cultural context, and individual differences.')}${card('Methods and Theory','RCC supports methodological and theoretical work that strengthens the study of religious cognition. Relevant approaches may include behavioral experiments, surveys, psychometrics, neuroimaging, computational analysis, qualitative research, conceptual modeling, secondary data analysis, and mixed methods.')}</div></div></section>
<section class="section alt"><div class="shell">${heading('Research Principles')}<div class="grid two">${card('Questions before methods','Projects begin with a clear question and use the methods best suited to answer it.')}${card('Multiple levels of explanation','We distinguish cognitive, psychological, neural, social, and cultural explanations while examining how they interact.')}${card('Claims proportionate to evidence','We avoid both reductionism and overinterpretation. Findings should support conclusions, not merely decorate them.')}${card('Religious diversity','Research questions and samples should not treat one religious tradition as the default model of religion when broader comparison is possible.')}</div></div></section>
<section class="section"><div class="shell"><div class="callout"><h2>Have a research question that would benefit from interdisciplinary collaboration?</h2><a class="button primary" href="/collaborate">Propose a Collaboration</a></div></div></section>`,
'/projects':()=>`${hero('Projects','RCC organizes its work through defined research projects. Each project has a focused question, a designated leadership team, an appropriate methodological plan, and a clear set of anticipated outputs. Individual projects may be led by different principal investigators, while the Collaborative provides a continuing framework for project development, coordination, and dissemination.')}
<section class="section"><div class="shell">${heading('Current Work')}<div class="empty-state"><span class="status">In Development</span><h2>Current project information is being prepared for public release.</h2><p>The approved project title, summary, leadership, and funding-status language will be posted after verification and authorization.</p></div></div></section>
<section class="section alt"><div class="shell">${heading('From question to completed work','Projects may begin with an investigator, a dataset, a funding opportunity, or a research problem that requires expertise across fields. RCC helps define the question, 